[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2506[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2507[0m:[38;5;10m[49m <!-- TODO: replace illustrative figures with measured results from the deployment. The ranges above are typical for digital care-coordination deployments augmenting human care management but vary substantially with program design, patient population, integration coverage, and engagement intensity. Published evidence on care-coordination interventions includes meta-analyses showing modest improvements on average with substantial heterogeneity by program; the strongest evidence is for hybrid programs combining AI-driven engagement with adequately-staffed human care management. -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2508[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2509[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Where it struggles:**
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2510[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2511[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Engagement attrition.** Patients (and caregivers) who stop responding lose the benefit. Mitigation: engagement-quality optimization across cadence, channel, content, and tone; per-cohort attrition monitoring; care-management intervention for high-attrition-risk cases; channel-mix experimentation; content relevance tuning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2512[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Reaching the patients who need it most.** The patients with the greatest coordination needs are often the patients with the least access to and comfort with digital tools. Mitigation: multi-channel deployment (SMS-first as the dominant channel for reach, voice-channel option, multilingual support from day one), integration with care-management for the highest-need cases, the assistant complementing rather than replacing human outreach.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2513[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cross-organizational integration coverage gaps.** A patient whose specialist is at an unconnected health system is a patient with a partial picture. Mitigation: explicit integration-coverage tracking with patient-and-caregiver-visible disclosure of what the assistant does and does not see; HIE/TEFCA participation where available; patient-and-caregiver self-report for the gaps; ongoing institutional integration roadmap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2514[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Provenance and freshness drift.** Data ingested today is stale tomorrow. Mitigation: explicit freshness tracking per source, disclosure of staleness in conversation, freshness-aware seam-detection, periodic re-pulls from authoritative sources.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2515[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Duplicate orders, conflicting orders, and care-plan discrepancies between organizations.** A patient with care from four health systems will accumulate these. Mitigation: explicit duplicate-detection and conflict-detection in the seam-detection rule library, surfaced to clinicians with the supporting evidence rather than auto-resolved.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2516[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Acute-event detection in a coordination context.** A patient surfacing acute symptoms (chest pain, severe shortness of breath, suspected stroke) needs immediate routing to acute care; the coordination context is the wrong context for acute-symptom triage. Mitigation: continuous emergency screening that runs on every utterance regardless of conversation context; immediate routing to triage workflow (recipe 11.6) or direct emergency contacts.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2517[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Mental-health-crisis disclosures during coordination conversations.** Coordination conversations regularly surface caregiver burden, patient distress, suicidal ideation, and other mental-health concerns. Mitigation: continuous mental-health screening with crisis-pathway routing (988, institutional crisis line); integration with mental-health support pathway (recipe 11.8); regular sampled review of distress-flagged conversations.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2518[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Caregiver-patient misalignment.** A caregiver saying things the patient does not want said, a patient withholding things from a caregiver, conflicting accounts of medications or symptoms. Mitigation: per-speaker proxy-access discipline, sensitive-record carve-outs, explicit speaker-discrimination in the conversation log, role-and-tone check at output safety.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2519[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Care-team workflow misalignment.** Alerts the care team cannot act on are alerts that erode trust. Mitigation: alert design with care-team feedback in production; alert-rate monitoring with thresholds for alert fatigue; per-cohort and per-care-team review of alert quality; named operational ownership at care-management leadership.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2520[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cross-organizational consent posture decay.** Consent given a year ago for one data source may need refresh as the patient's circumstances change. Mitigation: periodic consent-refresh cycle, patient-controlled consent dashboard, explicit consent-refresh prompts at care-event milestones.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2521[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Self-reported information dishonesty.** Patients underreport non-adherence, caregivers underreport burden, both occasionally over-report symptoms in pursuit of attention. Mitigation: outcome correlation against actual prescription fills, biometric data, encounter records, and downstream events rather than relying solely on self-report; relationship-quality engineering to reduce the perceived consequence of honest disclosure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2522[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Cultural and linguistic gaps.** Coordination practices that work for one demographic may not transfer to others. Mitigation: per-language and per-cultural-context content development with clinical-leadership review; per-cohort outcome and engagement monitoring; community-advisor involvement in protocol design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2523[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Privacy concerns and surveillance flavor.** Patients and caregivers may experience the coordination assistant as intrusive, especially in cross-organizational contexts. Mitigation: explicit engagement-policy enforcement, patient-and-caregiver-controlled opt-out granularity, periodic engagement-fatigue monitoring with cadence adjustment, transparent data-handling disclosure.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2524[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Outcome-attribution challenges.** Engaged patients are not a random sample; the patients who engage are different from the ones who do not. Mitigation: matched-cohort or quasi-experimental outcome analysis; per-engagement-strata outcome stratification; recognition that observational outcome correlation is suggestive, not causal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2525[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Long-term-relationship maintenance.** Patients and caregivers who have been in the assistant relationship for years may experience saturation. Mitigation: structured engagement-cadence reviews, periodic patient-and-caregiver feedback solicitation, content-refresh cycles, and (in some products) periodic human-care-manager interactions to revitalize the relationship.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2526[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Regulatory positioning shifts.** FDA guidance on patient-facing digital health continues to evolve; the institutional positioning may shift. Mitigation: regulatory-strategy artifact reviewed regularly; architectural changes preserve flexibility for either non-regulated or registered SaMD positioning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2527[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Care-team concerns about assistant autonomy.** Some clinicians are concerned about an AI tool engaging with their patients between visits, especially across organizational boundaries. Mitigation: clinical-leadership ownership and signoff at every level (protocol templates, individual-patient protocol activation, alert thresholds, scope discipline), care-team visibility into all assistant interactions, robust feedback mechanisms, conservative-bias defaults.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2528[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Insurance and billing complexity.** Coordination services may or may not be reimbursable depending on payer, condition, and program structure (CPT codes for chronic care management, principal care management, transitional care management, complex care management, remote patient monitoring, behavioral-health integration; alternative-payment-model arrangements for accountable-care organizations and risk-bearing payers). Mitigation: institutional revenue-cycle and contracting team involvement from program design.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2529[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Adversarial inputs.** Patients (or others) attempting to extract information, manipulate recommendations, manipulate the proxy-access posture, or test the system. Mitigation: input-safety pipeline with prompt-injection detection; output-safety pipeline with scope verification; tool-Lambda enforcement of patient_id and caregiver_id arguments against the verified session; per-language jailbreak-test corpus.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2530[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Health-equity disparities.** Per-cohort monitoring may reveal that the coordination assistant reaches and benefits some populations more than others. Mitigation: per-cohort monitoring as launch-gate; periodic clinical-quality review with explicit equity focus; targeted outreach and content adaptation for underserved populations; community-advisor involvement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2531[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2532[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2533[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2534[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## Why This Isn't Production-Ready
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2535[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2536[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pseudocode and architecture above demonstrate the pattern. A production deployment needs to close several gaps that are intentionally out of scope for a recipe.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2537[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2538[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organizational integration coverage with named per-source ownership.** The largest pre-deployment investment is the cross-organizational integration work, which is multi-quarter for each new source. Each EHR, each HIE, each payer claims feed, each pharmacy API, each home-health vendor API, and each lab feed has its own onboarding, authentication, data-mapping, provenance-recording, and operational-monitoring overhead. Named per-source ownership is required.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2539[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2540[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Coordination-protocol library as architectural primitive with clinical-leadership signoff.** The coordination-protocol library (transition-of-care protocols, referral-tracking protocols, post-discharge protocols, post-procedure protocols, medication-reconciliation protocols, condition-specific coordination playbooks) is the institutional product. Each protocol has an effective date, a version, an owner at clinical leadership, indications and contraindications, and an annual review cycle.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2541[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2542[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Seam-detection rule library with versioning, owner, and per-rule launch-gate.** The seam-detection rule library is the largest non-LLM engineering investment. Each rule has a version, an owner (clinical leadership for the clinical-pattern rules; operations for the workflow-pattern rules; data engineering for the data-quality rules), indications, and a launch-gate threshold for false-positive and false-negative rate.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2543[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2544[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Provenance-journal discipline as architectural floor.** Every data point ingested is recorded with source, timestamp, ingestion path, and integrity hash. Every assistant assertion about coordination state is grounded in cited provenance with explicit age. Sampled review specifically tags ungrounded-claim and stale-data-claim as failure modes.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2545[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2546[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Caregiver-as-first-class-participant identity model with state-law compliance.** Caregivers have separate identities, separate authentication, separate proxy-access scope, separate sensitive-record-carve-out posture, and separate state-law access compliance. State-specific caregiver-consent and proxy-access laws vary substantially. The identity model and the consent-management infrastructure are reviewed by counsel familiar with each state in which patients reside.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2547[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2548[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Cross-organizational consent posture with regulatory-counsel review.** The consent posture covers HIPAA, the ONC Information Blocking and Interoperability rules, TEFCA participation requirements, state medical-record statutes, state caregiver-consent and proxy-access laws, 42 CFR Part 2 (substance-use treatment), state mental-health-record protections, state HIV-record and genetic-test-result protections, state adolescent confidentiality, and (where the assistant produces clinical recommendations) the FDA SaMD framework. <!-- TODO: verify; specific obligations vary by jurisdiction and continue to evolve -->
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2549[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2550[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **FDA-strategy artifact with regulatory-counsel review.** The institutional regulatory positioning is documented, reviewed by FDA-experienced regulatory counsel, and maintained as the deployment evolves. Patient-facing care-coordination software with cross-organizational integration sits at the intersection of multiple regulatory frameworks.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2551[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2552[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Care-management workforce sized appropriately, with named operational ownership.** The human care-management workforce (employed or contracted nurse case managers, social workers, care coordinators) is sized to the patient population, the expected escalation volume, and the per-state licensure requirements. The assistant complements rather than replaces the workforce. Under-sized capacity is a safety gap and a missed-coordination-value gap.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2553[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2554[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Per-cohort monitoring as launch-gate primitive.** Engagement, attrition, citation-coverage, scope-violation, ungrounded-claim, faithfulness-failure, role-or-tone-failure, structured-output-schema-failure, referral-closure-rate, transition-completion-rate, medication-reconciliation-accuracy, escalation-rate, equity-disparity flags, and outcome metrics vary by language, channel, condition, age cohort, sex, social-determinant flags, integration-coverage tier, and engagement intensity. Per-cohort dashboards reviewed by clinical leadership, operations, compliance, regulatory, and patient-experience teams.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2555[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2556[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Outcome-correlation pipeline as multi-quarter to multi-year post-launch commitment.** The pipeline pulls subsequent encounter records, claims data, prescription fills, lab results, patient-and-caregiver-reported outcomes, and downstream events. Coordination-outcome attribution is harder than chronic-disease attribution because the assistant operates across many seams; the analysis is suggestive rather than causal.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2557[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2558[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Multi-language deployment with validated translations.** Per-language asset development includes validated coordination-protocol translations, validated patient-education translations, validated regulatory-disclaimer translations, per-language tone calibration, and per-language equity monitoring.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2559[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2560[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Eligibility check and off-ramp for excluded populations.** Patients in active hospice (where a hospice-specific coordination tool is more appropriate), patients whose primary coordination is delivered by a contracted external care navigator, minors in adult-only deployments, and others as defined by clinical-leadership policy are routed to appropriate alternative care, not enrolled in the assistant.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2561[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2562[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Disaster-recovery topology with cross-organizational integration resilience.** When any of the integrated sources is unreachable, the assistant degrades gracefully: it discloses the affected coverage gap to the patient and caregiver, it does not claim to know what it cannot verify, it preserves the conversation, and it re-syncs when the source returns. Per-source failover is documented and tested quarterly.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2563[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2564[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Compensation operations for inappropriate responses, including cross-organizational data-mismatch responses.** When a patient, caregiver, or clinician disputes a response, the operations team reproduces the conversation, retrieves cited content and provenance, and either confirms the assistant followed protocol or identifies the deviation and feeds the failure mode into the improvement loop.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2565[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2566[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Build-vs-buy rigor.** Several mature commercial vendors offer care-coordination products. Most major institutions run a hybrid: build the institution-specific protocol-library, seam-detection-rule, and consent-management layers in-house, partner with vendors for the cross-organizational integration plumbing, and partner with care-management staffing vendors for the human workforce.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2567[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2568[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Operational ownership across multiple teams.** The assistant sits at the intersection of clinical leadership across primary care, hospital medicine, specialty practice, pharmacy, home health, and care management; the cross-organizational data-integration team; the care-management workforce; compliance, regulatory, and legal; IT and security; the call center; patient experience; the malpractice carrier; and (in some institutions) the equity, patient-advocacy, and community-engagement offices.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    2569[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
